Describe a time when you had your first mobile phone / Describe a smartphone. You should say
- What it was like
- When you had it
- Who gave you the cell phone
- Explain how you felt about it

I received my first mobile phone about 7 years ago, just before starting high school. At that time, I had taken the entrance examination and was accepted into one of the most prestigious high schools in my province. My parents were proud of me, so they decided to buy me a smartphone as a reward for my hard work. To be honest, I was over the moon.

I remember my mother taking me to a well-known mobile shop in my area. I looked around for a while, checked out several models, and eventually chose an Oppo phone. I was aware of my family's financial situation and didn't want this purchase to become a burden for them. Therefore, I selected a smartphone that was within their budget. Despite that, I was very satisfied with it, as it offered many useful features for both my studies and entertainment.

Getting a phone significantly changed my daily routine. I used it to keep up with the news and quickly search for information online. It also helped me stay connected with my family and friends, no matter how far apart we were. In my free time, I would occasionally play games on it as a way to unwind after a long day at school.

Having said that, the smartphone had some negative impacts on my life as I overused it and became addicted to social media. I hardly hit the hay before midnight, so that I had to wear glasses due to my extreme short-sightedness. My parents had to strictly manage my screen time. This method did wonder for me since I could spend less time using my phone and more time on studying.

However, using a smartphone also had some negative effects on my life. I became overly reliant on it and gradually developed a habit of scrolling through social media for hours. I often stayed up past midnight, which eventually affected my eyesight and forced me to wear glasses. To address this, my parents imposed strict limits on my screen time, which turned out to be very effective, allowing me to focus more on my studies.

Even though it no longer works, I still keep it in my drawer as a meaningful reminder of my parent's unconditional love.
